04422nam a22005295i 9780822396284DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223962847 a10.1515/97808223962842doi  a(DE-B1597)552739  a(OCoLC)1229161258  a(OCoLC)1226679634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a3271 aHevia, James L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCherishing Men from Afar :bQing Guest Ritual and the Macartney Embassy of 1793 /cJames L. Hevia. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b6 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1 Introduction -- t2 A Multitude of Lords: The Qing Empire, Manchu Rulership, and Interdomainal Relations -- t3 Planning and Organizing the British Embassy -- t4 King Solomon in All His Glory: The British Embassy in China -- t5 Guest Ritual and Interdomainal Relations -- t6 Channeling Along a Centering Path: Greeting and Preparation -- t7 Convergence: Audience, Instruction, and Bestowal -- t8 Bringing Affairs to a Culmination -- t9 Guest Ritual and Diplomacy -- t10 From Events to History: The Macartney Embassy in the Historiography of Sino- Western Relations -- tAppendix -- tGlossary of Chinese Characters -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late eighteenth century two expansive Eurasian empires met formally for the first time-the Manchu or Qing dynasty of China and the maritime empire of Great Britain. The occasion was the mission of Lord Macartney, sent by the British crown and sponsored by the East India Company, to the court of the Qianlong emperor. Cherishing Men from Afar looks at the initial confrontation between these two empires from a historical perspective informed by the insights of contemporary postcolonial criticism and cultural studies.The history of this encounter, like that of most colonial and imperial encounters, has traditionally been told from the Europeans' point of view. In this book, James L. Hevia consults Chinese sources-many previously untranslated-for a broader sense of what Qing court officials understood; and considers these documents in light of a sophisticated anthropological understanding of Qing ritual processes and expectations. He also reexamines the more familiar British accounts in the context of recent critiques of orientalism and work on the development of the bourgeois subject. Hevia's reading of these sources reveals the logics of two discrete imperial formations, not so much impaired by the cultural misunderstandings that have historically been attributed to their meeting, but animated by differing ideas about constructing relations of sovereignty and power. His examination of Chinese and English-language scholarly treatments of this event, both historical and contemporary, sheds new light on the place of the Macartney mission in the dynamics of colonial and imperial encounters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aDiplomatic etiquettezChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822396284zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822396284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822396284.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles